post_text:
PV News
The 5th and 6th grade classes at Pine Village Elementary have been studying the brain. They identified the main parts of the brain, their functions, and how they are connected to learning. They learned that brain neurons are “chatty” and like to share new knowledge and make connections to existing knowledge. Brain wrinkles are good. And, that the old saying “practice makes perfect” is really good advice since repetition is how the brain learns to master a skill. Their culminating activity was an opportunity to dissect sheep brains!

-Emma Nern and Aubry Herbert look at the various brain parts.
-JD Bennett, Conner Harris, Wrede Johnson, and Ethan Voigt take a closer look at a sheep brain.
-Emma Tarkington is very intrigued by the two hemispheres of the sheep brain.
-Hayden Sparenberg cautiously examines the sheep brain before dissecting.
-Alex Piercy has found the three main parts of the brain.

Pine Village Elementary will have a new home for the beginning of the 2023-2024 school year. Design and planning has started (pictures are preliminary drawings not final construction documents). The school will be located to the west of the existing building and include a student/community workout area and historical components of the existing school. Exciting times for the Pine Village Community and Warren County Schools!

Feel free to contact the district office for more information and for questions about this project - 762-3364.

Seeger Memorial Junior - Senior High School
February 19 at 10:03 AM ·

On Tuesday, February 18th, Purdue University announced the launch of the Purdue Fast Start program, an opportunity for Indiana high school students to earn up to a year of free college credit from Purdue University. Here are the basics:

Students who pass a minimum of five College Level Examination Program (CLEP) exams will be assured admission to Purdue University.
Modern States (the online learning platform for advanced-placement courses) provides more than 30 free online courses to help students prepare for CLEP exams.

A $1 million gift from the founder and CEO of Modern States, Steve Klinsky, and his wife Maureen will cover the cost of 10,000 CLEP exam fees for Indiana students.

You can learn more by visiting purdue.university/faststart, or calling 765-494-1776 (800-743-3333 for hearing impaired).

Pine Village place 4th in State Science Bowl

The Pine Village 6th Grade class recently competed in the IASP Science Bowl competition. The competition consisted of three rounds: an experiment round, a team round, and an individual round (4 team members are selected to complete this part). Scores from each round are included in the final placement score. The PV sixth graders finished 4th in the state in their division. The team was coached by Mrs. Kim Markley. Great job Pine Knots!

shared_text:
Seeger Memorial Junior - Senior High School
January 22 at 9:07 AM ·

Seeger is proud to be the ONLY emerging Early College high school in the area!

The Early College program allows Seeger students to graduate with a block of 30 college credit hours that will transfer to any Indiana State Educational Public Institution.

Credentialing changes from the Commission for Higher Education have required Seeger staff members to complete extra coursework to be eligible to offer this program to our students. We are thankful for a dedicated staff that is willing to continue their education and the Warren County Community Foundation, Inc. for providing a grant opportunity to help assist with tuition costs.

Click here for more information about the Early College program: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1UZV25rVLaNb0nj4Rj0ziUW32K_kdM2oaAampphJLsHI/edit?usp=sharing

Seeger Memorial Junior - Senior High School
December 4, 2019 at 9:40 AM ·

A little update on Hanah Wolf’s fundraiser: Hanah organized a penny war for Warren Central Elementary School which took place on the week of November 18th. The third-grade classes won and will receive a cookie party on Friday, December 6th! The elementary helped to contribute a total of $658.40 to go towards the funds for Parkinson’s Research. She will be holding a shoe drive January 6th-January 17th. There will be collection sites in Seeger and the proceeds will continue to go towards Parkinson’s Research! Raffle tickets will be sold during every home Friday and Saturday boys game. She has raised over $1,000 and hopes to raise even more before April 2020! Hanah asks that you continue bringing in medicine bottles! She has collected around 800 bottles so far and will be making periodical shipments while keeping a running total! Hanah wants to give this great community the biggest thank you possible, it could not happen without you all! Stay tuned for more updates!

Who doesn’t love a good math mystery?
PV 6th graders are working diligently at computing fractions in order to solve the mystery of “Who has the best Growth Mindset?”.

Tucker Herndon, Nick Wallpe, and Garrett Wontor choose a quiet location to work as a team - they know how to help themselves be successful!

40 Kylie Payne and Adeline Dietrich share ideas and strategies - having a growth mindset is important to being a team player!

Conor Eberly, Kayden Shaw, and Jaedyn Garcia compare answers. When they don’t match, they view their mistakes as a chance to learn!

Seeger Memorial Junior - Senior High School
January 21, 2019 at 10:16 AM ·

Seeger staff and students are raising money for the Leukemia and Lymphoma Society through Thursday, 1/24/19. The staff member with the most money in their bucket will have a pie thrown in their face. Send your change with your Seeger student to raise money for a good cause. This could be the first time CH has had a pie thrown in her face in 2019!

The Leukemia and Lymphoma Society is the worlds largest voluntary health organization dedicated to fighting blood cancer. The LLS’s mission is: cure Leukemia, Lymphoma, Hodgkin’s disease, and Myeloma, while also improving the quality of the lives of patients and their families. All donations given to the LLS go straight towards blood cancer research.

The Leukemia and Lymphoma Society is the worlds largest voluntary health organization dedicated to fighting blood cancer. The LLS’s mission is: cure Leukemia, Lymphoma, Hodgkin’s disease, and Myeloma, while also improving the quality of the lives of patients and their families. All donations given to the LLS go straight towards blood cancer research.
